{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"f7bbf6e4-7273-452b-8ca9-83b863e0311f","content":"Add a `.vscode/mcp.json` file (or edit the existing one) in your workspace root:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- `type: \"stdio\"` means Copilot communicates with your server via stdin/stdout.\n- `command`/`args` tell VS Code how to launch your server.\n- After saving, open the Copilot chat in agent mode — it will auto-discover the tools your server exposes.\n\nIf you need environment variables, add an `\"env\"` object alongside `\"command\"`. For a pre-built DLL, replace the command with `\"dotnet\"` and args with `[\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]`.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"2c9a2c9a-d780-417d-a9c6-cc618ba9426b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to know how to configure `mcp.json` to use their C# MCP server with GitHub Copilot in VS Code agent mode. Let me provide a concise answer based on my knowledge of VS Code MCP configuration.","outputTokens":303,"requestId":"2C0D:2ED2CA:28EA279:2D4827D:69FD3636"},"id":"abd4947f-2bee-467a-875b-7d9ea9a4c805","timestamp":"2026-05-08T01:02:54.729Z","parentId":"7e1f0636-467a-419c-ae0e-023f1432cc5d"}
